    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-07T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-07T15:00:00-05:00" n="913"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d913">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> papers, “Meetings with the
                    President”</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of State</hi>
                </head>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">[Extract]</note>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1954-07-07T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 7, 1954—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>2. The President read <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Syngman Rhee</persName>’s letter
                    to me of July 2.<note n="1" xml:id="d913fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1818">p. 1818</ref>.</note> He
                    indicated he thought that President <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>
                    was being rather arrogant in <pb facs="0711" n="1829" xml:id="pg_1829"/>
                    attaching conditions to acceptance of the President’s possible invitation. We
                    discussed the possibility of getting the <persName corresp="#p_VFLGJA1">Van
                        Fleet</persName> recommendations before making a definitive reply to
                        <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s request for additional Korean
                    divisions. I said that I thought if he came he would want to come before
                    Congress adjourned so as to be able to appear before a joint session. That made
                    the timing difficult. The President said he doubted that <persName
                        corresp="#p_VFLGJA1">Van Fleet</persName>’s recommendations on this subject
                    would be very important. He was good as a field general but not as a planner. I
                    said I would try to find out the Defense Department’s views with a view to
                    drafting a reply to <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> in the light
                    thereof.</p>
                <p>. . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
        </body>
